ce:section.ce:para:
The mechanism of the reaction involves the dehydration of β CD molecules under hydrothermal conditions where water acts as a hydrolytic medium. The presence of high concentrations of hydroxide ions (OH
−
) and hydrogen ions (H
+
) promotes the dehydration process, leading to ring opening by generating electron-deficient carbon species. These species are capable of accepting electrons from the nitrogen atom of sericin. As a result, sericin’s N-atom gets easily incorporated to form a N-doped graphitic structure through ring-closing approaches. This process seems to involve a complex interplay of chemical reactions, likely occurring in a hydrothermal environment where temperature and pressure play crucial roles in facilitating the reactions
